Personal immunity (*ratione personae*) refers to immunity granted to **specific individuals** (e.g., heads of state, diplomats) **regardless of whether their conduct was public or private**, distinguishing it from functional immunity (*ratione materiae*), which depends on the nature of the conduct. This aligns with the principle that immunity is tied to the person’s status, not the context of their actions.
